This seems to be a classloading issue.

Your weblogic.xml has `&lt;package-name&gt;org.glassfish.jersey.*&lt;/package-name&gt;`
i.e. it loads Jersey by an application classloader, but `weblogic.jaxrs.server.media.multipart.Jersey1MultiPartSupport` is loaded by a different (WLS default) classloader. So the class cast exception.

The fix would be in your **weblogic.xml**. There are a few options you can try:

 1. Update your `prefer-application-resources`. For start, add    
```
&lt;resource-name&gt;META-INF/services/org.glassfish.hk2.extension.*&lt;/resource-name&gt;
&lt;resource-name&gt;META-INF/services/org.glassfish.jersey.*&lt;/resource-name&gt;
&lt;resource-name&gt;META-INF/services/org.glassfish.jersey.internal.spi.*&lt;/resource-name&gt;
...
&lt;resource-name&gt;jersey.repackaged.org.objectweb.asm.*&lt;/resource-name&gt;
&lt;resource-name&gt;org.glassfish.jersey.*&lt;/resource-name&gt;
```
2. Remove Jersey from `prefer-application-packages`. In 14c, there is a newer Jersey and it can possibly satisfy your needs, especially in the current 14.1.2.
3. As a last option, bundle in `Jersey1MultiPartSupport` and update `prefer-application-packages`. Not a good solution, but depends on your use-case.

